As far as Montague and his comment that my military analogy was &quot;simply wrong&quot;, I will kindly offer that you would gain more credibility with audience if you would actually back up your next baseless and pointless comment. However, without some form of logical refutation I cannot counter your non-argument, and this may be your goal. <br>
<br>
I posit that my analogy was spot on. Refer to the later &quot;produce offspring&quot; line as to what you should not be doing if you cannot wrap your brain around it.<br>
<br>
Lastly, if you cannot understand analogies, perhaps some basic mathematical style logic.<br>
<br>
Parents meet. Parents mate. Parents have kid. Kid blows away 17 people in his high school one day.<br>
<br>
Remove the &quot;Parents mate&quot; portion of the sequence. What happens? No kid around to blow away 17 people in his high school.<br>
<br>
Even if you boil it down to basic math-style proofs and words of two syllables or less, the parents will still be the root cause of any action of their offspring.<br>
<br>
Still, I prefer to call the parents on the carpet for this incident because, like my fictional military commander in the analogy, they neither kept a close enough watch on their errant son, nor did they train the child adequately to deal with the minimal pressures of teenage life.<br>
<br>
Still, all in all, Crackanna said it best with her &quot;it's their fault because they did not fulfill their responsibilities&quot; line. <br>
