e parents and the child are to blame.  <br>
<br>
Parents do have a responsibilty to be involved in their child's life.  How you discipline your kid should depend on the age/maturity of the child, his/her personality, and what is most likely to influence his or her behavior.  That *gasp* means actually spending time with and getting to know your child.  Spanking a toddler for running out in the street after you warned him/her that a car was coming is quite different than spanking a teenager for stopping at McDonald's on the way home from the movies without calling to let you know that he/she would be home later than promised.  Like Crackanna said, the punishment should fit the crime.  It shouldn't be a show of force or abuse of power.  Kids respect firmness as long as it's fair.<br>
<br>
I have to come to the defense of social workers.  They have a hard job to do.  Most of them are not as weak, as liberal, or as easily manipulated as portrayed in the media.  Spend a little time at a sheltered workshop, a shelter for battered women, a homeless shelter or soup kitchen, a halfway house, a drug rehab center, a nursing home, an orphanage, or a juvenile detention center and see for yourself.  Social workers have some really tough clients and problems to deal with.  Don't judge them all based on the mistakes of a few.  No, I am not a social worker but I know one quite well... my mother.<br>
<br>
Lastly I have a philosophical question for you.  Do you believe that there are the evil people in the world?  I mean truly evil people.  Is it possible that even with the best parents that a kid can just be plain bad? <p><a href="http://216.118.107.63/SIGS/juror.jpg" target="_blank">
